ph_descripcion: Photo by @daisygilardini | The Norwegian archipelago of Svalbard lies midway between Norway and the North Pole. One of the last real Arctic wildernesses, it has breathtaking landscapes and teems with wildlife—polar bears, foxes, reindeer, walruses, whales, and all sorts of bird life. Almost 60 percent of the archipelago is covered by glacier ice, which unfortunately—as elsewhere on the planet—is disappearing due to climate change. I photographed this wonderful blue iceberg while cruising one of the many fjords. Follow me @daisygilardini for more images and behind-the-scenes stories. #svalbard #iceberg #arctic #conservation #climatechange

ph_descripcion: Photo by @nicholesobecki | The steep, winding road to the top of Jebel Hafit is the desert’s answer to California’s famed Highway 1, attracting roadsters, bikers, and hikers from across the globe. This is the highest mountain in Abu Dhabi and one of the highest in the United Arab Emirates. An extension of Al Ain, the first site in the Emirates to be designated as a UNESCO World Heritage site, Jebel Hafit has been inhabited since prehistoric times. In the Al Ain oasis at the base of the mountain rest tombs dating back thousands of years. Today, Al Ain continues to thrive, hosting a population of more than half a million people who keep this ancient caravan route alive. | Abu Dhabi welcomes you. It is a cultural destination that embraces creativity and exchange, inspiring your curiosity. @visitabudhabi and connect with what matters to you. #InAbuDhabi

ph_descripcion: Photo by @MichaelGeorge | In November, the sunsets in Antarctica last for hours and hours. Typically from around 9 p.m. to 1 a.m., you’ll experience some form of twilight. On this evening there was a perfect mix of conditions. Still water reflecting the sky below, delicately broken pack ice, and a distant wind whipping up the snow on the mountains made for an idyllic landscape. For more photos and writing from my travels, follow along @MichaelGeorge. #antarctica #antarcticpeninsula #icebergs #iceberg #glacier

ph_descripcion:
Photo by @francescolastrucci | Near the town of Yangshuo, I climbed to the top of Moon Hill at sunrise to get a view of the peaks emerging like ghosts from the early morning mist. The province of Guangxi is another China—that of an ancient Chinese print, that of the thousands of foggy, cloud-submerged karst peaks emerging from the rivers and the plain, all covered by an intense green.

Over the centuries the dreamlike landscape has inspired generations of artists and has become so iconic that it has been reproduced even on the Chinese 20 yuan banknote.

Follow me @francescolastrucci for more places, daily life, and stories around the world. #china #mountains #landscape

ph_descripcion: Photo by @nicholesobecki | I’ve always admired the geometric patterns of Islamic art, the aesthetic quality of repeating and interlaced shapes elegantly spilling out. Qasr Al Watan, Abu Dhabi's Palace of the Nation, was built to pay homage to Arabian heritage and design. The lavish building remains a working presidential palace, used to welcome foreign leaders, but also open to public tours since 2019. This mirrored installation in the Great Hall of the palace broke up the neat, patterned space, both amplifying and disrupting its formal artistry. Here, Mohamed Hijari looks through a window of the display—an unexpected encounter that remakes the famed hall into a fresh kaleidoscope of color and shape. The perfection of the palace’s original design was lost, but something else was gained. | Abu Dhabi welcomes you. It is a cultural destination that embraces creativity and exchange, inspiring your curiosity. @visitabudhabi and connect with what matters to you. #InAbuDhabi

ph_descripcion: Photo by @BabakTafreshi | When I created The World at Night (@twanight) project in 2007 with an international team of night-sky photographers, one of our main aims was to protect the last remaining natural night skies by using photos and stories to communicate the value of this essential part of our nature. This is one of those places: La Palma, Canary Islands, where the night sky is protected by law. The locals appreciate this preserved heritage that has made their island an icon and astrotourism destination. Here, the Milky Way’s bright core stands above seaside salt production ponds in a 20-second exposure. See more night-sky wonders @BabakTafreshi. #darkskies #twanight #canaryislands #astrotourism

Photo by @mattborowick | Icebergs float freely down the Ikaasakajik (Greenlandic) river, part of Scoresby Sound in eastern Greenland. The iceberg in the foreground is massive, towering a few hundred feet high at least. But when positioned near the mountains on both sides of the river, it looks rather small. The mountains are around 6,000 feet (1,828 meters) tall, so you can really imagine how it feels standing there.
This image was created during a licensed drone flight and was taken in accordance with local regulations. Please follow for more pictures like these at @mattborowick. #iceberg #greenland #mountains #nature #arctic

ph_descripcion: Photo by @sofia_jaramillo5 | Photographer David Ryder looks up at an opening in Ape Cave near Mount St. Helens in Washington State. The cave is actually a lava tube that’s 2.5 miles (four kilometers) long, the third longest lava tube in North America and pitch-black aside from the openings on either end and beneath the natural skylight pictured here. Every year, thousands of visitors flock to the caves and other volcanic features around Mount St. Helens, called Lawetlat'la by the Indigenous Cowlitz people and known as Loowit or Louwala-Clough by the Klickitat. For more images from the Pacific Northwest and around the world, follow @sofia_jaramillo5. #caves #apecave #PNW

ph_descripcion: Photo by @nicholesobecki | For me, no morning is complete without a cup of coffee, and I often travel with my beans and press—but not on this assignment. Emirati culture is steeped in this dark brew. Bedouins traditionally toasted the beans over a desert fire before grinding them by hand and infusing the beans with the fragrant addition of cardamom. Later, this ritual moved to the home, where offering a qahwa—coffee prepared according to Arabic tradition—was an important gesture of welcome and hospitality. In Abu Dhabi today, you’re more likely to find cutting-edge roasteries like this one at Blacksmith Coffee Company, where Jefferson Olivas checks the color of the beans as they warm. I loved experiencing the balance these makers have found, remaining rooted in tradition while looking to the future. | Abu Dhabi welcomes you. It is a cultural destination that embraces creativity and exchange, inspiring your curiosity. @visitabudhabi and connect with what matters to you. #InAbuDhabi

ph_descripcion: Photo by @nicholesobecki | Rock gives birth to sand as tiny fragments break away, freed from their unmoving geological origin. Along their journey their hard edges soften, polished by the wind to smooth perfection. Arriving at Rub’ al Khali, or the Empty Quarter, I was moved to silence by its harsh, vast beauty. Though life there is sparse today, legends of a lost city, the Atlantis of the Sands, persist. Also known as Ubar, Wabar, and Iram, the fabled site has long fascinated and frustrated explorers, archaeologists, and scholars. Following the dunes with my eyes, I try to picture this long dreamed of civilization swallowed by the enormity of its environment. | Abu Dhabi welcomes you. It is a cultural destination that embraces creativity and exchange, inspiring your curiosity. @visitabudhabi and connect with what matters to you. #InAbuDhabi

ph_descripcion: Photos by @stephen_matera | Maligne Lake is a popular spot in the Canadian Rockies. I was there during the day, and there were many people in the area hiking, paddling, and exploring. When I went back in the evening, it had cleared out entirely, and I couldn't believe I had the place to myself—or so I thought. I was shooting photos as the light was getting better and better. Around the time I took this image, I heard a rustling noise in the shoulder-high willows behind me, which gave me a jolt of adrenaline. I turned around to see a very healthy brown bear feeding in the willows only 30 feet (nine meters) away from me. Exciting and scary as that was, I was torn about moving because the light was so good! I moved away and was able to watch the bear from a safe distance for half an hour in the fading twilight. Follow me @stephen_matera for more images like this from Canada and around the world. #CandianRockies #NationalPark
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on February 12, 2023. May be an image of mountain, nature and lake.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @MichaelGeorge | The snowy sheathbill is the only land bird that’s native to Antarctica. They were also the only birds to take up temporary residence on our ship deck. Throughout our journey on the Antarctic Peninsula, we would often find small groups of sheathbills gathered on the deck and railing, wandering around. Though quite cute, they do leave behind a memory of their visit in the form of little white spots. Not so fun for the crew to clean up on the regular. For more photos and writing from my travels, follow along @MichaelGeorge. #antarctica #antarctic #snowysheathbill #glaciers #ice

ph_descripcion: Photo by @nicholesobecki | Keeper Mohamed Hassan leads an Arabian camel across the sands of Abu Dhabi’s Rub’ al Khali, or the Empty Quarter, taking two steps for each of the dromedary’s long lopes. When driving along, this camel farm seems to appear out of nowhere, the world’s largest sand desert stretching out from it in all directions. Observing the pair’s uneven progress, I thought about how vast landscapes such as this have bound humans and camels together. Where lesser animals might perish, camels bring you where you need to go, producing white, frothy milk even in punishing conditions. In Bedouin tribes they were given to a bride’s family as dowry. Poets from these communities were common, and the animal they’d sing about the most? The camel. | Abu Dhabi welcomes you. It is a cultural destination that embraces creativity and exchange, inspiring your curiosity. @visitabudhabi and connect with what matters to you. #InAbuDhabi

Photo by @jessicasample | The McKee Botanical Garden, a subtropical botanical garden in Vero Beach, features 18 acres (7 hectares) of more than 10,000 native and tropical plants, including one of Florida's largest collections of water lilies. Once part of a larger, family-owned attraction, the landscape was on the verge of development when local volunteers and the Trust for Public Land stepped in to restore and preserve it. Today, it's a serene place to stroll through a royal palm grove, around waterfalls and tranquil streams, or through the jungle-themed Children's Garden. From McKee you can hop over to the beautiful turquoise water of the Vero Beach shoreline. | From swimming in freshwater springs to paddling through mangroves and exploring hidden caverns, adventure awaits you in Florida. @visitflorida

ph_descripcion: Photo by @acacia.johnson | A brown bear nurses her cubs in Alaska’s McNeil River State Game Sanctuary, where more brown bears gather to fish each summer than has been observed anywhere else on Earth. Due to abundant food sources, a vast untouched habitat, and careful management of human visitors over time, these bears have come to view people as a neutral presence. You know a wildlife encounter is a success when the animals are completely at peace with your presence. The incredible trust shown by this mother bear was a powerful reminder of what human-animal encounters can be like when wilderness is truly protected—and what makes the sanctuaries and refuges of the Alaska Peninsula some of the best places to see brown bears safely in the wild. | In Alaska, extraordinary experiences are an everyday occurrence. From glacier trekking to wildlife tours to learning about Alaska Native culture, awe-inspiring adventures await @travelalaska

ph_descripcion: Photo by @paoloverzone | The tallest adobe structure of its kind in the world, the minaret of the Agadez Mosque in Niger rises like a beacon above the desert at the end of the day. It stands 27 meters (88 feet) tall and served as a watchtower for centuries, guarding the Tuareg city of Agadez against enemies and welcoming caravans during their travels. The mosque was constructed in the 16th century, and its charm has remained unchanged since that time. Follow @paoloverzone for more images and stories.

ph_descripcion:
Photos by @krisgraves | Expedition Everest – Legend of the Forbidden Mountain is an impressive attraction at Disney’s Animal Kingdom Theme Park. In an area made to resemble a Tibetan village at the base of Mount Everest, we were immersed in details from the region. The village came to fruition following multiple research trips to Nepal and surrounding areas. The whole of Disney’s Animal Kingdom is the product of extensive research. The level of detail and storytelling is incredible. We also had a chance to watch the Imagineering team test techniques for creating village walls throughout Disney’s Animal Kingdom.

I was given the opportunity to capture life from behind the scenes at Walt Disney World Resort. Stay tuned for more of what makes Disney possible in the coming weeks and months. The Walt Disney Company is majority owner of National Geographic Partners. @WaltDisneyWorld @DisneyParks @natgeointhefield #DisneyWorld50

ph_descripcion: Photo by @jessicasample | Located about an hour outside the city of Oaxaca, high in the mountains, Hierve el Agua is the site of petrified waterfalls and calcified natural springs balancing on the edge of a steep cliff. ph_descripcion: Photo by @amivitale | A tower of reticulated giraffes seeks shelter under trees in the shrubby landscape of the 850,000-acre (344,000-hectare) Namunyak Wildlife Conservancy in northern Kenya. Giraffes, unfortunately, are in trouble. Giraffe populations have dropped in the past three decades, plummeting from approximately 155,000 in the late 1980s to about 110,000 in 2020. Reticulated giraffes number fewer than 16,000. The decline is thought to be caused by habitat loss and fragmentation and some poaching. Learn more, including how to help, by following @r.e.s.c.u.e, @sararafoundation, and @amivitale for more stories. #protectgiraffes #DontLetThemDisappear #giraffe #savegiraffes #kenya

ph_descripcion: Photo by @nicholesobecki | Musicians like Faisal Al Saari are expanding on ancient traditions, weaving together Emirati oud music and a vast sampling of global sounds. The oud is one of the oldest instruments of its kind in the world, believed to date to the Akkadian Empire in ancient Mesopotamia, now present-day Iraq. Passed down through generations, the oud remains at the core of modern Arabic music. Al Saari, an Emirati musician and composer, has spent three decades mastering these age-old sounds. He is also among the first musicians to adapt the instrument to play Bach, flamenco, and jazz—bringing music from around the world to his home in multicultural Abu Dhabi. | Abu Dhabi welcomes you. It is a cultural destination that embraces creativity and exchange, inspiring your curiosity. @visitabudhabi and connect with what matters to you. #InAbuDhabi

One explorer, Alexander von Mörk, was so spellbound he wanted his ashes buried here. After he died in World War I, they were. Photo by @DaisyGilardini | The Falkland Islands (Islas Malvinas) mark the northernmost limit of the king penguin range. In the morning flocks of penguins gather on the beach before heading out to sea to feed. Kings aren’t picky eaters exactly, but they’re very specific about what they hunt and catch. They eat small, schooling fish like lanternfish (myctophids) year-round, especially during breeding season. When the weather grows colder they eat more icefish and cephalopods—mollusks, octopus, and squid—to supplement their winter diet.

This image/video was created during a licensed drone flight and was taken in accordance with local regulations. Follow me @DaisyGilardini for more images and stories from behind the scenes. #FalklandIslands ##climatechange #kingpenguin #conservation

ph_descripcion: Photo by @carltonward | Juniper Creek winds through pine forest in Blackwater River State Forest, near Pensacola. The rivers of Northwest Florida are among my favorite places to paddle for day trips or overnight camping on wide, sandy banks. This landscape is part of the largest contiguous longleaf pine ecosystem left on the planet and vital to the Florida Wildlife Corridor—a connected network of green space that includes 10 million acres (four million hectares) of public parks and preserves interspersed by eight million acres (three million hectares) of working forests, ranches, and croplands. | From swimming in freshwater springs to paddling through mangroves and exploring hidden caverns, adventure awaits you in Florida. @visitflorida

ph_descripcion: Photo by @joshuacogan | Haida carver Stormy Hamar helps his granddaughters experience the feeling of a traditional canoe during a summer day last year. Carving canoes out of single large pieces of cedar is a craft that Stormy has been at the forefront of reviving through his dedication and passion. Photo by @francescolastrucci | It is difficult for Corleone, Sicily, to escape its stereotypes, but beyond its cinematic clichés is the real city of Corleone, rich in history, culture, faith, traditions, and friendly people. Called the city of a hundred churches, Corleone's historic center owes its splendor to its maze of alleys and the presence of precious and fascinating palaces and buildings of worship. Corleone's anti-Mafia documentation center houses some of the most important testimonies of the fight against the Mafia in Sicily. The surrounding wilderness offers breathtaking landscapes.

A few months ago, I had the pleasure to hike across the island of Sicily, Italy, starting from the North coast town of Palermo and following the paths to the South coast town of Agrigento. Long forgotten, this 9 days long walk was once part of the famous and over a thousand years old trans-european Via Francigena and it’s now a newly revived ancient pilgrimage route. Carrying the name of “Magna Via Francigena” it shows the traces that Greeks, Romans, Arabs and Aragonese left throughout history in this Sicilian crossroad.
Follow me @francescolastrucci for more places, daily life, and stories around the world. #sicily #italy #dailylife #documentaryphotography

ph_descripcion: Photo by @nicholesobecki | The soft pinks and purples of early dawn color the gray mangroves of Jubail Mangrove Park, a haven for species native to Abu Dhabi and birds migrating between Africa and Eurasia. Even beyond wildlife, the value of this ecosystem is immense. Coastal forests like this one function as blue carbon sinks, storing up to 10 times more carbon than their green counterparts on land (and holding it in the soil and sediment even after a tree dies). Not far away, the morning hustle was gaining pace amid towering skyscrapers, but here the lesson was one of quiet resiliency. As our world prepares for rising temperatures and seas, scientists hope that the adaptability of these mangroves—already facing abnormally high salt levels in their shallow tidal waterways, as well as wild temperature swings—will emerge in more ecosystems elsewhere in the world. | Abu Dhabi welcomes you. It is a cultural destination that embraces creativity and exchange, inspiring your curiosity. @visitabudhabi and connect with what matters to you. #InAbuDhabi

Photo by @DaisyGilardini | Prion Island, in South Georgia’s Bay of Isles, is one of the main breeding sites for wandering albatrosses and is specially protected as a result. Wandering albatrosses are one of the world’s largest birds, with a wingspan of up to 3.5 meters (almost 12 feet). They are listed as vulnerable on the IUCN Red List of Threatened Species. Major threats include longline fishing, bycatch fisheries, and climate change.

Wandering albatrosses are monogamous and breed every second year. The chick is fledged after roughly 10 months. It’s impressive to witness young albatrosses test their wings before flying for the first time. Follow me @daisygilardini for more images and behind-the-scenes stories. #southgeorgia #albatross #wanderingalbatross #conservation

Built in the middle of a rectangular pool of "amrit" (holy water), it is believed to have healing powers and also gives name to the city of Amritsar. Also known as Harmandir Sahib, the temple is the most sacred site in the world for Sikhs. The complex has four entrances oriented according to the four cardinal points to symbolize the belief of the Sikh in equality and to welcome all people regardless of religion or provenance into their holy place to experience one of the most tangibly spiritual places in India. As visitors walk in circles around the marble pavement that surrounds the sacred pool, enchanting music induces a constant yet delicate state of trance. ph_descripcion: Photo by @mattborowick | One of the most important things to remember when hiking around Greenland is that you always need to stay on your toes and be alert. We came upon a small herd of sleeping musk oxen, and while they are not carnivores, they will still attack when they feel threatened in any way. An adult musk ox can reach speeds of just under 40 miles per hour (64 kilometers per hour), and after watching a few of them run uphill, I can say for sure that we wouldn’t have stood a chance. While we may have been a bit too close for comfort at times, we respected the space and knew when we had overstayed our welcome. Please follow for more pictures like these at @mattborowick. #nature #greenland #muskox #arctic #wildlife

ph_descripcion:
Photos by @andrea_frazzetta | The Appian Way is among National Geographic Travel’s 2023 Best of the World destinations, highlighted as one of the best trips for immersing yourself in history and heritage.

The Appia is the most famous Roman road still in existence. It was one of Europe’s first highway systems and inspired the phrase "All roads lead to Rome." But its legacy has been largely neglected and its stones buried under millennia of history. Now a government project is under way to transform the Appia into a pilgrimage crossing from Rome to the sea on the heel of Italy’s boot, bringing thousands of visitors strolling across the wide, flat basalt stones.

Check out the list of all 25 breathtaking places at the link in bio. To see more photos from my travels, follow me @andrea_frazzetta.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @daisygilardini | I am totally in love with the Svalbard reindeer. How could you not be, when it has such a cute muzzle? These reindeer are endemic to Svalbard and have adapted well to survive the harsh environment. Because they are sedentary, their energy demands are low, especially in winter, when food is scarce and they have to rely on their reserves of body fat. Their expected lifespan is around 10 years. One cause of death is starvation due to worn-out teeth from grazing on sparse vegetation mixed with gravel. Follow me @DaisyGilardini for more images and stories behind the scenes. #reindeer #svalbard #wildlifephotography #polar #climatechange

ph_descripcion: Photo by @michaelgeorge // In Puerto Rico, El Yunque National Forest is filled with stunning hikes. One of the most rewarding and accessible is the short journey up to Mount Britton Tower. I began the trek standing in the shadow of a dense forest of palms. The trail vacillates between the welcome shade of the cloud forest and open areas filled with island sun. Though the distance isn’t far, I found myself energized by the challenge of this mostly vertical walk. Any huffing and puffing is well worth it, as the tower provides a gasp-worthy 360-degree view. Constructed in the 1930s, the stone structure provides visitors with a view of both the Atlantic Ocean and the Caribbean Sea. I could see the rainforest blending slowly into the coastline, with various cities resting in the valleys. After taking it all in, I sauntered down the spiral staircase and back into the cool embrace of the trees below. // The beautiful island of Puerto Rico has more to offer beyond its beaches. From welcoming locals to 500-year-plus history, dare to @discoverpuertorico and its many treasures. #DiscoverPuertoRico
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on December 19, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @rubensalgadoescudero | Farmers play chinlone at night after a long day on the field in Pa Dan Kho village in Myanmar. Chinlone, also called caneball, is Myanmar's national sport. This ancient traditional game typically focuses more on teamwork than competition. It is played around a circle and consists of the players using their feet and legs to pass the ball, keeping it in the air. Hands are normally not allowed to touch the ball. Played for more than 1,500 years, chinlone is a tradition that is very much alive today. Follow me @rubensalgadoescudero to see the world through my lens. #myanmar #chinlone #caneball #sport

ph_descripcion: Photo by @daisygilardini | A polar bear swims in open water during a mild summer day in the Svalbard archipelago. Midway between Norway and the North Pole, Svalbard is one of the last real Arctic wildernesses. Polar bears are incredibly good swimmers. Their average speed is 10 kilometers per hour (six miles per hour). The longest swim ever recorded was that of a subadult female that swam 426 miles (686 kilometers) over a period of nine days. Bears try to avoid long-distance swims when they can, though, because of the amount of energy expended while swimming. Unfortunately, due to the warming climate and the consequent loss of sea ice, long swims are becoming more frequent. While adult bears are protected from the cold water by a thick layer of fat (up to 11 centimeters, or 4.3 inches, in most cases), younger, skinnier bears and older bears are often at risk of hypothermia, which leads to drowning. Follow me @daisygilardini for more images and behind-the-scenes stories. #polarbear #conservation #svalbard #arctic #climatechange
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on December 05, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @babaktafreshi // At 69ºN latitude, well inside the Arctic Circle, this fjord near Tromsø, Norway, is an incredible spot from which to view the northern lights. When I hiked down to the shore on this crystal clear March night, the aurora was completely absent, but after a few hours of patience in the cold, this impressive, earlike swirl suddenly formed near midnight. My heart was beating like a drum. It was hard to take my eyes off of the scene and concentrate on the camera. Thanks to the moonlight, the five-second exposure was long enough to reveal the landscape but not so long that it diffused the fast-moving aurora pattern. The lights occur when electrically charged particles interact with gases in the upper atmosphere. They are drawn by Earth's magnetic field to the polar regions. // When you dare to explore the unfamiliar, you feel more alive. Choose adventure and discover the thrill of getting outside this winter with @5gum.
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on December 02, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @kahliaprilphoto // The first light of day touches the Ten Peaks on a crisp winter morning at Moraine Lake in Banff National Park. A familiar sight for many in the summer months, this magical lake takes on a completely different look as it transitions into winter. With road access closed, getting to the lake becomes a 26-kilometer (16-mile) journey on foot. Timing is everything to photograph and experience the changing light while the lake is completely frozen but not yet covered with snow. Setting off in the dark in the early hours with a headlamp, I took a chance on this cold, clear morning, and everything came together. // When you dare to explore the unfamiliar, you feel more alive. Choose adventure and discover the thrill of getting outside this winter with @5gum.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @amivitale | Llamas wade in the waters of Montana's Swan Lake, a popular fishing and recreational area in a remote part of the state. This outfitter’s llamas were brought to Montana in 1979 to help move timber-cruising equipment. Seeing what great trail companions and sure-footed mountaineers they were, the group began to offer commercially guided pack trips to Glacier National Park (@glaciernps) and the surrounding areas in 1981. Follow @amivitale for more stories about our connections to the natural world. #montana #llamas #trekking #camping #wilderness

ph_descripcion: Photos by @taylorglenn | In-camera multiple exposures create abstracted views of aspen trees during the peak of fall. This is a fun technique for creating something a little different with your images. There isn't an exact science to it, but rather it can be more of an experiment. I exposed the scene over five different captures while slightly moving the camera, which then automatically layered the images together. Sometimes it works and sometimes … Well, you just have to play with it. For more from fall in Wyoming and beyond, follow @taylorglenn. #AspenTrees #FallFoliage #Wyoming
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on November 11, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by Luján Agusti @lujanag | Lago Escondido, Tierra del Fuego, Argentina. Portrait of Josefina Bronzovich holding her dog Ella. Like most of her family, Josefina grew up surrounded by a wonderful natural environment, where she learnt the love for horses and nature. Josefina and her cousins still maintain a strong connection with the land where they grew up despite living in the city. I documented the life and work of @baqueanostdf, in South Patagonia. Follow me @lujanag to learn more about life and traditions in the Island of Tierra del Fuego.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @MichaelGeorge | The harried modern world slips away as soon as you cross over to the breathtaking coastline of St. Abb's Head National Nature Reserve. Its landscape is visual poetry, as the cliffs themselves are the result of volcanic activity from tectonic plates crashing into one another. Throughout the year, wildlife ranging from gray seals to kittiwakes call this area home and utilize these natural features to raise their young. I walked to an outlook, with the sea many feet below, and imagined these hillsides in spring, when it is said they are covered in an assortment of colorful native wildflowers. While hiking along the soaring heights of the bluffs, you might even spot a dolphin or a whale. Just be sure to bring your binoculars! For more photos and writing from my travels, follow along @MichaelGeorge. #scotland #visitscotland #stabbshead #naturereserve #coastal
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on November 06, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by Luján Agusti @lujanag / Lago Escondido, Tierra del Fuego, Argentina. Aurelia and Josefina ride on horseback with their family along the shores of Lago Escondido (Hidden Lake). Its name comes from the fact that it is located in a deep valley in the Andes Mountains, about 40 miles (60 kilometers) from the city of Ushuaia and surrounded by forest. The lake’s shores are partly made up of stone walls and a scarce presence of aquatic vegetation. I documented the life and work of @baqueanostdf in southern Patagonia. Follow me @lujanag to learn more about life and traditions in Tierra del Fuego.
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on November 05, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photos by @hellokrisdavidson | Día de los Muertos in Mexico is a gently festive time when departed loved ones are welcomed back home for a visit. Trails of marigolds line the streets, golden petal paths created to guide the returning souls. As a travel photographer, I am frequently asked what my favorite assignment has been. It is an impossible question! But I always end up talking about Día de los Muertos and the ancient wisdom and grace that the holiday encompasses. Included here are Dia de los Muertos scenes from Mexico City, Huaquechula, and Oaxaca. #diadelosmuertos #Mexico #CDMX #Oaxaca
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on November 01, 2022.

Photo by @irina_sigl_photography | Congratulations to Irina Sigl on becoming the September 2022 @natgeoyourshot Photographer of the Month! Each month, we select a Your Shot Photographer who produced stunning work and fostered a sense of community.

The dragon is the symbol of Ljubljana, the capital of Slovenia. It is proudly enthroned on the city's coat of arms and on the Dragon Bridge named after it. The beautiful art nouveau bridge is decorated with four huge bronze dragon figures. When I visited the bridge during my stay in Ljubljana, the cloud cover was spectacular. One of the clouds looked like a fire cloud that one of the dragons was spewing out. I just had to place it correctly, and the illusion of the fire-breathing dragon of Ljubljana was perfect! Nikon Z7, 30mm, f8, 1/125s, ISO100. #YourShotPhotographer #Slovenia #Ljubljana
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on October 31, 2022.

ph_descripcion:
Photo by @amivitale | Meet my llama friends. They're Montana locals who love having their picture taken. Photographing curious and affectionate llamas is like photographing people. The more time you spend with them, the more open they become. And animals, just like people, need to accept you before you can make great images of them. One secret is to never look at them directly. Animals often perceive eye contact as aggression, so if you cover one eye with your hand or your camera, they feel less threatened.

Llama-trekking is one of the many activities available in remote parts of Montana. Llamas have padded feet and can eat a wide variety of vegetation. Their impact is similar to that of deer. They are also alert and sure-footed, making them ideal and helpful companions for toting gear to Swan Lake, an area outside of Glacier National Park (@glaciernps).

Follow @amivitale for more stories about our connections to the natural world. #montana #llamas #trekking #camping #wilderness
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on October 30, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @MichaelGeorge | Bowhill is a meticulously preserved 18th-century historic house in the heart of the Scottish Borders. A pedestrian path takes you through an oversized iron gate, acting as a preamble to the grandeur of the house itself. The property is so atmospheric, my mind conjured a classical soundtrack in time with my steps. When I entered the Victorian kitchen, restored in the 1970s, I was astounded by the size of the hearth and the soft color palette of the all-copper cookware. Bowhill facilitates a step into the past, and now managed by the Buccleuch Living Heritage Trust, the stunningly preserved house stands as a monument to conserving the Scottish countryside for future generations to enjoy. For more photos and writing from my travels, follow along @MichaelGeorge. #scotland #visitscotland #bowhill #scottishborders
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on October 30, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photos by @kiliiiyuyan // The Pacific Northwest is known for being wet, but up on Mount Baker, all that precipitation comes down as snow instead. In fact, Mount Baker holds the record for the most snowfall over a single winter season. Over time, that snow packs down into glacial ice. On our Mount Baker adventure, chef Melissa King and I took my handcrafted, traditional kayaks to Upper Bagley Lake and trekked about in the snow to forage for berries and other flavors of the alpine tundra. Mount Baker has many different ecosystems from bottom to top, including lush forests and alpine meadows filled with wildflowers. It’s a terrific journey to follow the Nooksack River all the way up to the snow, where it all starts. The mountain has several names in the Salish family of languages. It’s known as Kwelshán by the Lummi and Nooksack peoples, who share its lands and hold deep relationships with the mountain. // The #MazdaCX50 is purpose-built to connect you with nature. After all, it’s on unpaved dirt and gravel paths where our sense of wonder comes alive. The first-ever Mazda CX-50. We’re more human in nature.
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on October 28, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photos by @kiliiiyuyan // With its beaches and palm trees, the Big Island of Hawaii is a classic Pacific island—but there’s a lot more to it when you get in deeper. From the bright yellow tangs and vibrant corals at Kealakekua Bay to the great volcano Mauna Loa, where the weather’s cooler closer to the stars, the Big Island is a place to get properly immersed in the natural world. It’s the largest (and youngest) of the Hawaiian Islands, called Moku o Keawe by native Hawaiians, after a chief known to his people for establishing peace and prosperity. // The #MazdaCX50 is purpose-built to connect you with nature. ph_descripcion: Photos by @kiliiiyuyan // With its beaches and palm trees, the Big Island of Hawaii is a classic Pacific island—but there’s a lot more to it when you get in deeper. From the bright yellow tangs and vibrant corals at Kealakekua Bay to the great volcano Mauna Loa, where the weather’s cooler closer to the stars, the Big Island is a place to get properly immersed in the natural world. It’s the largest (and youngest) of the Hawaiian Islands, called Moku o Keawe by native Hawaiians, after a chief known to his people for establishing peace and prosperity. // The #MazdaCX50 is purpose-built to connect you with nature. After all, it’s on unpaved dirt and gravel paths where our sense of wonder comes alive. The first-ever Mazda CX-50. We’re more human in nature.
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on October 25, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by Michael Yamashita @yamashitaphoto | “Bullet Train,” Brad Pitt’s latest action comedy film, takes place on Japan’s Tokaido Shinkansen, the busiest high-speed train line in the world. Operating between Tokyo and Osaka, this was the first bullet train line in Japan, opened in 1964, just in time for the Tokyo Olympics. Before the Shinkansen, a conventional train traveling between Tokyo and Osaka took six hours and 30 minutes to complete the trip. Now the latest N700 bullet trains, with maximum speeds up to 300 km per hour (180 miles per hour), can complete the trip in as little as two hours and 25 minutes. Pictured here, the Shinkansen zooms past towering Mount Fuji, the highest mountain in Japan. Can’t wait to see the movie. #bullettrain #Shinkansen
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on October 23, 2022.

ph_descripcion:
Photos by @MichaelGeorge | I could feel my legs burning as I cycled up to the grand overlook of Scott's View. This was one of Sir Walter Scott's favorite places to visit and sit for reflection. I welcomed the well-placed bench to catch my breath and take in the sweeping landscape, featuring Eildon Hill, an impressive formation made up of volcanic rock. Visitors can walk, cycle, or drive to this point to see the many geological features of the area. In late summer, you might even find a selection of fresh blackberries ready to be picked from the bushes at the top.

As I ambled along the River Tweed, a looming structure began to take shape in the distance. The Leaderfoot Viaduct, seen in the second image, is an iconic structure not far from the town of Melrose. The viaduct stands around 126 feet (38 meters) above the water and, because of its scenic placement, is a popular stop for travelers on the Four Abbeys Cycle Route. There are walking paths all around that allow visitors to take in the architecture from various angles. Though it is no longer in use, the viaduct was operated as part of the Berwickshire Railway from 1865 to 1948. On this clear day, I could easily imagine a steam train humming along the horizon. For more photos and writing from my travels, follow along @MichaelGeorge. #scotland #visitscotland #scottsview #leaderfootviaduct #cycling
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on October 19, 2022.

ph_descripcion:
Photo by @andrea_frazzetta | Rome’s third-century Arch of Drusus marks the informal start of a planned 360-mile (580-kilometer) walking route along the Appian Way. Although it may not seem like it, this scene is in the heart of Rome, a few hundred meters from the Baths of Caracalla.

The Appian Way is the most famous Roman road still in existence. It was one of Europe’s first highway systems and inspired the phrase "All roads lead to Rome."

But its legacy has been largely neglected, and its stones buried under millennia of history. Now a government project is under way to transform the Appia into a pilgrimage crossing from Rome to the sea on the heel of Italy’s boot, to bring thousands of visitors strolling across the wide, flat basalt stones.

To see more photos from my travels, follow me @andrea_frazzetta. #Italy #appianway #Roma
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on October 15, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @daisygilardini | Harp seals in the Gulf of Saint Lawrence in Québec, Canada, give birth to their pups on the pack ice in February and March each year. They are yellowish in color at birth but turn a pure white after a couple of days, hence the label whitecoats. Poor ice conditions over the past few years have deeply affected the pups’ mortality rates. Scientists say that while a single year of bad ice won’t affect the population unduly, poor ice patterns over a period of time could have a dramatic and worrying effect on the future of the species. Follow me @DaisyGilardini for more images and stories from behind the scenes. #harpseal #seal #Canada #magdalenislands

Photo by @rubensalgadoescudero | Sunset overlooking Thisa Wadi Temple in Bagan, one of my favorite places in the world to visit. Located about 600 kilometers (370 miles) from Yangon, Myanmar's largest city, this 11th-century kingdom once led by King Anawrahta boasted more than 4,000 temples. Although half of them have been destroyed because of earthquakes and man-made forces, more than 2,000 structures still survive today. Thisa Wadi Temple was commissioned by a queen in A.D. 1287.

I was supposed to go on a one-month trip to Myanmar in 2013. When I arrived, I immediately fell in love with the country and its people. I ended up staying for two and a half years. It is where I began my journey as a professional photographer.

Follow me @rubensalgadoescudero to see the world through my lens. #myanmar #bagan #buddhist #temple #pagoda
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on October 08, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @acacia.johnson | A traveler from an expedition ship stands on the sea ice off the coast of Spitsbergen in Svalbard, a remote archipelago about halfway between Norway and the North Pole. One of my favorite parts of traveling in the Arctic is learning firsthand about how sea ice forms the basis of the Arctic marine ecosystem. When I took this picture, we were exploring on foot and could feel the gentle ocean swell undulating beneath the ice—a reminder of the rich life underneath. ph_descripcion: Photo by @MichaelGeorge | The owner of the Outdoor Centre in Loch Insh, Scotland, has a particularly unique connection to the country’s waterways. Here is an excerpt from my article on this region: “One afternoon I met with the organizers of the Storylands Sessions, Merryn Glover and Hamish Napier, a local writer and a musician (seen in the second image of this carousel). These sessions promote the music and stories of the region, unearthing the many narratives that weave through the local community. As Merryn explains, it is drawing from the ancient tradition of ‘cèilidh,’ a Gaelic word for a gathering in people’s homes where bards, musicians, and storytellers once met to share poetry and songs. At one of their recent events, Duncan Freshwater told the story of his father’s legal battle for the right to navigate the River Spey. The case went all the way to the House of Lords in London, where he won when a 1782 case was cited that had established a Public Right of Navigation on the Spey, a victory that goes hand-in-hand with Scotland’s ‘right to responsible access.’ This ruling helped create the country’s cherished reputation for allowing adventurers to wild camp almost anywhere, as long as they travel responsibly, by treading lightly and leaving the land as they found it. Freshwater, a last name so fitting it feels like a wink, is one of the directors of the Loch Insh Outdoor Centre along with his two brothers.” For more photos and writing from my travels, follow along @MichaelGeorge. #scotland #badenoch #lochinsh #visitscotland #cairngorms
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on October 06, 2022.

ph_descripcion:
Photo by @andrea_frazzetta | In centuries past, the Appian Way symbolized the Roman Empire’s might. Now, Italy is restoring the ancient road, hoping to create a pilgrimage route through history and preserve the immense archaeological heritage spread along its path.

Here, the amphitheater of Santa Maria di Capua Vetere, the second biggest arena after the Colosseum, is also home to the first and most famous gladiator school. In this very area, the well-known revolt of Spartacus broke out in 73 B.C.

One of the most significant findings from the Appian Way thus far is a bust known as the Philosopher’s Head.

For more photos from the Appian Way, follow me @andrea_frazzetta. #Italy #appianway #Roma
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on October 05, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @hellokrisdavidson | A tree photographed through a car windshield during a thunderstorm on Sapelo Island, one of eight major barrier islands along the Georgia coast. Collectively, these barrier islands comprise an ephemeral landscape seemingly made of water, sand, and salt—a place shaped and governed by winds and tides. Sapelo Island is a stunningly beautiful and wild place, separated from the mainland by two sounds and nine-foot (three-meter) tides. There is no road to Sapelo—one must travel by air or water, and one must be invited. Today, most of the island belongs to Georgia and is managed by the state’s Department of Natural Resources. About a third of the island is a protected reserve where scientists study wildlife, including eagles, falcons, sea turtles, and other marsh creatures. Nestled inland is Hog Hammock, a seawater Gullah Geechee community. The few roads stretching across Sapelo are unpaved and without street signs or streetlights. Humanity’s presence feels fleeting here, as though nature might wash it away with a rainstorm. #Sapeloisland #gullahgeechee #Georgia
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 25, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @MichaelGeorge | Walking before the Great Tapestry of Scotland, I realized I could spend a whole day here and still miss many of the intricate details. Located in Galashiels, the tapestry is a massive, community-focused artwork made up of 160 panels that illustrate the history of Scotland, with topics ranging from wars and battles to Dolly, the famously cloned sheep. Each panel took more than 400 hours of stitching and, in total, a thousand people contributed their talents to bring it to life. I appreciated how the designers created panels to celebrate not just kings and saints but ordinary people as well. For more photos and writing from my travels, follow along @MichaelGeorge. #scotland #visitscotland #galishield #greattapestryofscotland #history

ph_descripcion:
Photo by @amivitale | A mother giraffe embraces her calf outside the small village of Doulouwal Peulh in Niger. In this small enclave 50 miles (80 kilometers) from the capital city of Niamey, people live side by side with the endangered West African giraffe in Niger's government defined Giraffe Zone. There are only about 600 West African giraffes left on the planet (up from a low of 49 in the wild, itself a conservation success).

In December 2018, the Giraffe Conservation Foundation, with the Niger government and other partners, endeavored to move eight of these highly threatened giraffes from the zone to Niger's Gadabedji Biosphere Reserve, from which they had been absent for more than 50 years. The translocation has been a huge success, and one of the giraffes has had a baby.

Learn more, including how to support those working to protect these creatures, by following @giraffe_conservation and @amivitale for more stories. #SaharaConservationFund #conservation #environmentalism #giraffes #niger
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 15, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photos by @hellokrisdavidson | When I gaze up at the night sky, at shimmering, faraway stars and constellations named after gods and mythical beings, I almost always think of this quote attributed to Anthony de Mello: “You have to understand, my dears, that the shortest distance between truth and a human being is a story.” Stretching from the past into the future, our stories make time travel possible. Combined with VR, space travel is within reach, too. Image 1: Artist Ryoji Ikeda’s LED light show of abstracted futuristic renderings reflected on a mirrored floor in a black room. Image 2: The Infinite, a NASA-inspired VR experience of a 3D model of the International Space Station. Image 3: Situated in West Texas, the McDonald Observatory is remote and blissfully free of light pollution. As one of the darkest places on Earth on a moonless night, it’s a perfect place to take in the night sky. #nightsky #timetravel #space
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 11, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @DaisyGilardini | A glorious end to the day in the Antarctic Peninsula as we approached the northern entrance of the Lemaire Channel at sunset. The channel is one of the most scenic locations in all of the peninsula. It stretches for 11 kilometers (seven miles) and is only 1.6 kilometers (one mile) wide at its narrowest point. The tallest peaks reach an altitude of 747 meters (2,451 feet) and include the Cape Renard Towers, a distinctive rock formation also known as Una Peaks. Follow me @daisygilardini for more images and behind-the-scenes stories. #antarctica #landscapephotography #sunset #climatechange #conservation

ph_descripcion: Photos of @natgeo filmmaker @bertiegregory by Will West | Our expedition to Antarctica for “Epic Adventures” was, without a doubt, the hardest shoot I’ve ever done. Although the crossing from South America to Antarctica is normally rough, once we arrive we tend to film in sheltered bays and channels. But the wildlife spectacle we were searching for this time happens out in the open ocean, away from shelter. Another issue was that wildlife gatherings are thought to be biggest at the end of the Antarctic summer. As summer turns to autumn, the amount of daylight shortens and the weather gets bad. We ended up having just six good filming days on our six-week expedition. When not filming, we spent most of our time clinging to our anchorage at the infamous Elephant Island. Here, I’m attempting to talk to the camera in a 70-mph (112-kph) gale. Filming for #EpicAdventuresWithBertieGregory, my new show now streaming on @disneyplus.
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 08, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by Luján Agusti @lujanag | Tierra del Fuego, Argentina. Veky hugs a small foal during hygiene tasks performed on the herd. Every year, near summer, all the farm animals receive health care. Their hair and nails are cut, and they are dewormed, among other things. For those who work in the Patagonian countryside, horses are great companions and allies. In the past, the relationship between human and horse was essential for the rider's survival and the completion of daily tasks, such as moving cattle for grazing, patrolling the territory, and creating new roads. I documented the life and work of @baqueanostdf, a tourism project carried out by a family of old settlers in southern Patagonia. Follow me @lujanag to learn more about life and traditions in Tierra del Fuego.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @amivitale | A mother brown bear and her cubs take a break from catching salmon at Katmai National Park and Preserve (@katmainpp) in southern Alaska. The park is known for its wild landscapes and for the many brown bears that gather in Brooks Falls to wait for salmon. Katmai is home to an estimated 2,200 brown bears. More bears than people are believed to live on the Alaska peninsula. “As many bear populations around the world decline, Katmai provides some of the few remaining unaltered habitats for these amazing creatures,” explains the @nationalparkservice. ph_descripcion: Photos by @bertiegregory and Will West | There are no prizes for guessing where a chinstrap penguin gets its name! In the second picture I’m filming a small chinstrap penguin colony at Point Wild on Elephant Island. This infamous point of land is where Shackleton left his men while he led a small group to find help after their ship had been crushed by ice. Against the odds, the mission was a success, and over four months later a Chilean naval ship came to the rescue! Filming for #EpicAdventuresWithBertieGregory, my new show coming to @disneyplus on September 8th.
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on August 28, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @daisygilardini | British Columbia’s Cascade Mountains are part of an international protected area that includes E.C. Manning Provincial Park, Skagit Valley Provincial Park, and Cascade Recreation Area, and extends south past the U.S. border to North Cascades National Park in Washington State. The region features a rich and wide variety of plants and wildlife because of differences in topography and geological variations. The mountain meadows are at their most beautiful during the wildflower blooming season in July and August. The variety of mountain flowers is stunning, from the bright red scarlet Indian paintbrushes to lupines, tiger lilies, crimson columbines, and fireweed. It’s simply a joy for the eyes! Follow me @daisygilardini for more images and behind-the-scenes stories. #canada #britishcolumbia #cascades #northcascades #landscapephotography
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on August 28, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @stephen_matera | Bald eagles perform a midair courtship dance along Hood Canal in Washington State. The bald eagle population has rebounded significantly since the mid-1960s, when the birds were on the brink of extinction. According to the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service, since 2009 bald eagle populations have quadrupled in the lower 48 states, where they now number more than 300,000. Follow me @stephen_matera for more images like this from Washington and around the world. #baldeagle #courtship #wildlife
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on August 27, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by Keith Ladzinksi @ladzinski | Warm light pours through Keyhole Arch in Big Sur, California. ph_descripcion: Photo by @bertiegregory | Lion cubs play in Zambia’s South Luangwa National Park. These cubs belong to a pride of lions that specializes in hunting African buffalo. Considering buffalo have huge horns, a grumpy attitude, and can weigh nearly 2,000 pounds (900 kilograms), taking them on is no easy task. So while this cub play might look like fun, it’s critical training for adulthood, when they’ll be helping the pride bring down lunch. Photographed for my new show, #EpicAdventuresWithBertieGregory, coming later this year to @disneyplus.
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on August 24, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @amivitale | A West African giraffe from Niger's Giraffe Zone, a government-defined region where giraffes and humans coexist, rests inside a boma before being translocated. There are only about 600 West African giraffes left on the planet (up from a low of 49 in the wild, itself a conservation success). In December 2018, the Giraffe Conservation Foundation, with the Niger government and other partners, moved eight of these highly threatened giraffes from the Giraffe Zone to Niger's Gadabedji Biosphere Reserve, from which they've been absent for more than 50 years. This is a hopeful story for an animal whose rapidly shrinking numbers are significant cause for concern. Follow @giraffe_conservation to learn more about what can be done to help giraffes, and @amivitale for more stories. #SaharaConservationFund #giraffe #savegiraffes #niger
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on August 23, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @francescolastrucci | At sunset, two men clean a gigantic Chinese fishing net in Fort Kochi, Kerala, India. Of the many that dotted the shore four decades ago, only half a dozen remain. Fishermen manually operate the nets according to the tides. At 10 meters (33 feet) high, the nets form an integral part of Fort Kochi’s landscape. It's believed they were introduced around the 14th century by merchants from the court of Kublai Khan. Follow me @francescolastrucci for more places, daily life, and stories from around the world. #kerala #india #dailylife
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on August 23, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @krystlejwright | One of the challenges of documenting storms is capturing lightning bolts. Some use a technology that helps trigger cameras each time a bolt is detected, while some, like myself, hold the camera and try to predict, firing off the shutter multiple times. It can be a frustrating process, since lightning can be random and unpredictable. However, with patience and perseverance the hard work eventually pays off. One of many highlights during the recent season of storm chasing in the American Midwest.
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Travel on August 21, 2022.
